    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1960-11-10T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1960-11-10T19:00:00-05:00" n="216"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d216">
                <head>216. Telegram From the Ambassador in Vietnam (<persName corresp="#p_DE1"
                        type="from">Durbrow</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                        State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d216fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 751K.00/11–1160. Limited Official Use Only. Received November 10,
                        9:25 p.m. This telegram was apparently not sent through Department of State
                        channels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Saigon</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1960-11-11T07:00:00+07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 11, 1960—7 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>998. Critic. Verbatim text. Embassy officer talked by phone with <gloss
                        target="#t_SECSTATE1">SecState</gloss> Presidency and Deputy <gloss
                        target="#t_SECSTATE1">SecState</gloss> Defense Thuan at 0610 at this house.
                        <persName corresp="#p_THUAN1">Thuan</persName>, who remains free, said he
                    talked with <persName corresp="#p_DIEM1">Diem</persName> 15 minutes earlier and
                    everyone at Palace safe at that point. <persName corresp="#p_THUAN1"
                        >Thuan</persName> understands paratroopers (apparently about one battalion)
                    mounted coup attempt as they had done in Laos.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_THUAN1">Thuan</persName> had report indirectly from
                    Reuters correspondent Russell that rebels using <gloss target="#t_PTT1"
                        >PTT</gloss> as headquarters. I had same report from <hi rend="italic"
                        >Time</hi> correspondent Wilde but personal observation by American official
                    about 0545 indicated area around <gloss target="#t_PTT1">PTT</gloss> quiet.
                        <persName corresp="#p_THUAN1">Thuan</persName> most interested receive that
                    report.</p>
                <p>Wilde told me at 0550 he had talked with a <persName corresp="#p_DLC1">Lieutenant
                        Colonel Dong</persName>
                    <note n="2" xml:id="d216fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_VVDLC1">Lieutenant Colonel Vuong Van
                        Dong</persName>.</note> who taking credit as coup leader. <persName
                        corresp="#p_DLC1">Dong</persName> believed to be Para-troop Battalion
                    Commander and said he spent four months at Leavenworth in 1958. Reported to be
                    30 years old. <persName corresp="#p_DLC1">Dong</persName> claimed control
                    airport, Presidential Palace, and other key points in city area. <persName
                        corresp="#p_DLC1">Dong</persName> reportedly told Wilde this is
                    anti-Communist coup mounted because the Diem government not effective enough in
                    dealing with present situation. <persName corresp="#p_DLC1">Dong</persName>
                    claimed all cabinet ministers captured. However, we talked subsequently to
                        <persName corresp="#p_THUAN1">Thuan</persName> and know that claim not true.
                    At 0620 <persName corresp="#p_CWE1">Colby</persName> from his house could tell
                    that Palace not yet seized but firing still continues in front of Palace and
                    situation appears to be at stalemate at moment. We thus believe <persName
                        corresp="#p_DLC1">Dong</persName>’s claims greatly exaggerated but outcome
                    still not certain.</p>
                <p>Radio Saigon broadcasting music about 0615 and thus apparently not under rebel
                    control.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Durbrow</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
